Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. The `link.final` file will be copied to the output and can\n# be used by downstream crates to get the linker flags of this\n# crate.\n\nmkdir -p target/{deps,lib,build,buildDeps}\nchmod uga+w target -R\necho  > target/link\necho  > target/link.final\n\n# Prepare crate dependencies\nfor i in ; Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. The `link.final` file will be copied to the output and can\n# be used by downstream crates to get the linker flags of this\n# crate.\n\nmkdir -p target/{deps,lib,build,buildDeps}\nchmod uga+w target -R\necho  > target/link\necho  > target/link.final\n\n# Prepare crate dependencies\nfor i in /nix/store/as268irmj7ybjj61x1l240y16jq15y80-rust_curl-sys-0.4.36+curl-7.71.1-lib /nix/store/44y4yjcmwwj050mxls6s9sfsb0mm9aw0-rust_libc-0.2.74-lib /nix/store/yzyb256r362lcbqkm6fy1abk218jb9xm-rust_openssl-probe-0.1.2-lib /nix/store/wvpwg0g7d0h9k4142883llbv1nl97avc-rust_openssl-sys-0.9.58-lib /nix/store/20c3lg926pszv53kplz9415b0w26sarn-rust_socket2-0.3.12-lib /nix/store/1bk473s6x8s6da5kz1plcj6gjh8fip3p-rust_libz-sys-1.1.0-lib /nix/store/gjjg5cqkvadb371wmzs8g83xaskbpmgh-rust_cfg-if-0.1.10-lib; This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. The `link.final` file will be copied to the output and can\n# be used by downstream crates to get the linker flags of this\n# crate.\n\nmkdir -p target/{deps,lib,build,buildDeps}\nchmod uga+w target -R\necho  > target/link\necho  > target/link.final\n\n# Prepare crate dependencies\nfor i in ; Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. The `link.final` file will be copied to the output and can\n# be used by downstream crates to get the linker flags of this\n# crate.\n\nmkdir -p target/{deps,lib,build,buildDeps}\nchmod uga+w target -R\necho  > target/link\necho  > target/link.final\n\n# Prepare crate dependencies\nfor i in ; For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. The `link` file is used for linkage in the current\n# crate. The `link.final` file will be copied to the output and can\n# be used by downstream crates to get the linker flags of this\n# crate.\n\nmkdir -p target/{deps,lib,build,buildDeps}\nchmod uga+w target -R\necho  > target/link\necho  > target/link.final\n\n# Prepare crate dependencies\nfor i in ; do\n  symlink_dependency $i target/deps\n  if [ -e \"$i/lib/link\" ]; then\n    cat $i/lib/link >> target/link\n    cat $i/lib/link >> target/link.final\n  fi\ndone\n\n# Prepare crate build dependencies that are used for the build script.\nfor i in ; do\n  symlink_dependency $i target/buildDeps\n  if [ -e \"$i/lib/link\" ]; then\n    cat $i/lib/link >> target/link.build\n  fi\ndone\n\n# Remove duplicate linker flags from the build dependencies.\nif [[ -e target/link.build ]]; then\n  sort -uo target/link.build target/link.build\nfi\n\n# Remove duplicate linker flags from the dependencies.\nsort -uo target/link target/link\ntr '\\n' ' ' < target/link > target/link_\n\n# Remove duplicate linker flags from the that are written\n# to the derivation's output.\nsort -uo target/link.final target/link.final\n\nEXTRA_BUILD=\"\"\nBUILD_OUT_DIR=\"\"\nexport CARGO_PKG_NAME=cc\nexport CARGO_PKG_VERSION=1.0.59\nexport CARGO_PKG_AUTHORS=\"Alex Crichton <alex@alexcrichton.com>\"\nexport CARGO_PKG_DESCRIPTION=\"\"\n\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_ARCH=x86_64\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_OS=linux\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_FAMILY=\"unix\"\nexport CARGO_CFG_UNIX=1\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_ENV=\"gnu\"\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_ENDIAN=little\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_POINTER_WIDTH=64\nexport CARGO_CFG_TARGET_VENDOR=unknown\n\nexport CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR=$(pwd)\nexport DEBUG=\"\"\nexport OPT_LEVEL=\"3\"\nexport TARGET=\"x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\"\nexport HOST=\"x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\"\nexport PROFILE=release\nexport OUT_DIR=$(pwd)/target/build/cc.out\nexport CARGO_PKG_VERSION_MAJOR=1\nexport CARGO_PKG_VERSION_MINOR=0\nexport CARGO_PKG_VERSION_PATCH=59\nexport CARGO_PKG_VERSION_PRE=\"\"\nexport CARGO_PKG_HOMEPAGE=\"\"\nexport NUM_JOBS=1\nexport RUSTC=\"rustc\"\nexport RUSTDOC=\"rustdoc\"\n\nBUILD=\"\"\nif [[ ! -z \"\" ]] ; then\n   BUILD=\nelif [[ -e \"build.rs\" ]]; then\n   BUILD=\"build.rs\"\nfi\n\n# Compile and run the build script, when available.\nif [[ ! -z \"$BUILD\" ]] ; then\n   echo_build_heading \"$BUILD\" cc\n   mkdir -p target/build/cc\n   EXTRA_BUILD_FLAGS=\"\"\n   if [ -e target/link.build ]; then\n     EXTRA_BUILD_FLAGS=\"$EXTRA_BUILD_FLAGS $(tr '\\n' ' ' < target/link.build)\"\n   fi\n   noisily rustc --crate-name build_script_build $BUILD --crate-type bin -C opt-level=3 -C codegen-units=$NIX_BUILD_CORES --edition 2018 \\\n     --cfg feature=\\\"default\\\" --out-dir target/build/cc --emit=dep-info,link \\\n     -L dependency=target/buildDeps  --cap-lints allow $EXTRA_BUILD_FLAGS --color always\n\n   mkdir -p target/build/cc.out\n   export RUST_BACKTRACE=1\n   BUILD_OUT_DIR=\"-L $OUT_DIR\"\n   mkdir -p $OUT_DIR\n\n   (\n     # Features should be set as environment variable for build scripts:\n     # https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/reference/environment-variables.html#environment-variables-cargo-sets-for-build-scripts\n     for feature in DEFAULT; do\n       export CARGO_FEATURE_$feature=1\n     done\n\n     target/build/cc/build_script_build > target/build/cc.opt\n   )\n\n   set +e\n   EXTRA_BUILD=$(sed -n \"s/^cargo:rustc-flags=\\(.*\\)/\\1/p\" target/build/cc.opt | tr '\\n' ' ' | sort -u)\n   EXTRA_FEATURES=$(sed -n \"s/^cargo:rustc-cfg=\\(.*\\)/--cfg \\1/p\" target/build/cc.opt | tr '\\n' ' ')\n   EXTRA_LINK=$(sed -n \"s/^cargo:rustc-link-lib=\\(.*\\)/\\1/p\" target/build/cc.opt | tr '\\n' ' ')\n   EXTRA_LINK_SEARCH=$(sed -n \"s/^cargo:rustc-link-search=\\(.*\\)/\\1/p\" target/build/cc.opt | tr '\\n' ' ' | sort -u)\n\n   for env in $(sed -n \"s/^cargo:rustc-env=\\(.*\\)/\\1/p\" target/build/cc.opt); do\n     export $env\n   done\n\n   CRATENAME=$(echo cc | sed -e \"s/\\(.*\\)-sys$/\\U\\1/\" -e \"s/-/_/g\")\n   grep -P \"^cargo:(?!(rustc-|warning=|rerun-if-changed=|rerun-if-env-changed))\" target/build/cc.opt \\\n     | awk -F= \"/^cargo:/ { sub(/^cargo:/, \\\"\\\", \\$1); gsub(/-/, \\\"_\\\", \\$1); print \\\"export \\\" toupper(\\\"DEP_$(echo $CRATENAME)_\\\" \\$1) \\\"=\\\" \\$2 }\" > target/env\n   set -e\nfi\nrunHook postConfigure\n",

For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. These flags are largely used for\n#   linking native libraries.\n#\n# The crate link flags are added to the `link` and `link.final`\n# files. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags. Two\n# kinds of dependencies are distinguished: build dependencies\n# (used by the build script) and crate dependencies. For each\n# dependency we have to:\n#\n# - Make its Rust library available to rustc. This is done by\n#   symlinking all library dependencies into a directory that\n#   can be provided to rustc.\n# - Accumulate linking flags.
